The Provider is expected to deliver the Provision across the Liverpool LEP area.

Additional information: The Contracting Authority intends to use an eTendering system in this procurement exercise. Suppliers Instructions How to Express Interest in this Tender~: 1. Register your company on the eSourcing portal (this is only required once): https://dwp.bravosolution.co.uk and click the link to register - Accept the terms and conditions and click 'continue' - Enter your correct business and user details - Note the username you chose and click 'Save' when complete - You will shortly receive an email with your unique password (please keep this secure) 2. Express an Interest in the tender - Login to the portal with the username/password - Click the 'PQQs / ITTs Open To All Suppliers' link. (These are Pre-Qualification Questionnaires or Invitations to Tender open to any registered supplier) - Click on the relevant PQQ/ ITT to access the content. - Click the 'Express Interest' button at the top of the page. - This will move the PQQ /ITT into your 'My PQQs/ My ITTs' page. (This is a secure area reserved for your projects only) -You can now access any attachments by clicking 'Buyer Attachments' in the 'PQQ/ ITT Details' box 3. Responding to the tender - Click 'My Response' under 'PQQ/ ITT Details', you can choose to 'Create Response' or to 'Decline to Respond' (please give a reason if declining) - You can now use the 'Messages' function to communicate with the buyer and seek any clarification - Note the deadline for completion, then follow the onscreen instructions to complete the PQQ/ ITT - There may be a mixture of online and offline actions for you to perform (there is detailed online help available) You must then submit your reply using the 'Submit Response' button at the top of the page. If you require any further assistance please consult the online help, or contact the eTendering help desk. This is a procurement for services under the Light Touch Regime and DWP will not be bound by Public Contracts Regulations 2015 except as such Regulations are applicable to the Light Touch Regime. DWP expressly reserves the rights: (i)to use a reverse auction; (ii)to cancel this procurement at any stage; (iii)to not award any contract as a result of the procurement process commenced by publication of this notice; (iv)to make whatever changes it may see fit to the content and structure of the tendering competition; (v)and in no circumstances will DWP be liable for any costs incurred by potential suppliers. column42:
Guildford Borough Council (“the Council”) has for a number of years, working alongside other agencies, provided a homeless outreach and support service within the Borough. The service has an established identity, Guildford HOST (Homelessness Outreach & Support Team). The Council has agreed funding of £819,600 to enable it to continue the provision of this important service between 1 July 2016 and 30 June 2021 and now wishes to procure the services of an organisation to manage and staff this service working alongside the Council and other agencies.
The service will offer: 
•	assertive outreach for vulnerable people rough sleeping, or at risk of rough sleeping 
•	support to people placed in HOST assessment beds 
•	interventions to prevent former rough sleepers who have secured accommodation from being evicted
•	resettlement support to former rough sleepers who have secured accommodation 

The service will follow the principles of good practice as defined by guidance issued by the Department of Communities and Local Governments (CLG) and local policies and protocols agreed by the Council. 

The Council’s current contract with Home Group Ltd will terminate on 30 June 2016 and there are four employees who the Council anticipate will TUPE to the new service provider.  
The Council considers that the minimum level of staffing required to deliver an effective service will be a full time manager (carrying a small caseload) and three frontline outreach workers.  The Council will require the option to participate in staff recruitment.

LOCATION 
It is anticipated that the majority of individuals the service will support, will be located in and around Guildford town centre.  However, the service must also be able to respond to the needs of those sleeping rough across the borough and there may be occasions where resettlement support is required to be delivered to clients assisted to secure accommodation in other areas, including outside Surrey.  
The service provider is required to have a base centrally located within Guildford town centre.

HEFCE has a statutory duty to ensure that the quality of education is assessed in the institutions it funds or is considering funding. The services covered by this tender will support a revised operating model for quality assessment and will include:
•	Review visits to test a provider’s ability to meet baseline regulatory requirements
•	Verification of a provider’s methodology for its own internal review process
•	Support for governing bodies to enable them to fulfil their responsibilities for academic governance
•	Investigations, where serious concerns about a provider have been raised
•	Exploration of approaches to the training of external examiners and to the calibration of standards

The services will be required to be delivered to locations across England and Northern Ireland. Some services may also be delivered to locations in Wales and/or Scotland.

It should be noted that the building within which the site is situated will be remain operational throughout the early stages of the contract period, and as such bidders should make allowances for carrying out noisy or disruptive works outside normal working hours. Furthermore, the University transport department will be temporarily sited within the Reception area for the duration of the works, and will remain operational throughout the contract – this means that staff and some students will be accessing this area to collect/drop off pool cars.

The works are located at the University of Derby Kedleston Road campus.


The work is to be completed in two distinct phases to allow for the space to be used for examination resits mid-way through the construction phase.
Phase 1: To comprise as a minimum the strip out and minor demolition works required, laying of new carpets, blocking up of openings, fitting of temporary doors (if permenant doors not available) and decorations – to be completed by no later than 2nd June 2016.
Phase 2: Completion of all outstanding works, including installation of AV, suspended ceilings, operable walls, M&E alterations etc to be commenced on 26th June with completion no later than 16th August.
Should the Contractor feel that more works can be completed safely and comfortably within Phase 1 this will be considered by the Employer.

The purpose of this tender is to put in place a framework agreement to procure asset management (coring)services which may be accessed to undertake coring works in highway reinstatements on the highway networks of bodies participatory to the framework. This will allow compliance with national reinstatement specifications, as given in the Specification for the Reinstatement of Openings in Highways (SROH) 1st, 2nd,3rd and future editions or updates to be determined. Providers must provide evidenced interpretive reports documenting certain physical properties of each of the cores taken. All core extraction, sampling and testing shall be carried out by a UKAS accredited laboratory approved to undertake such tests in accordance with the procedures of the relevant British or European standards. Providers must be accredited for the appropriate work categories under the United Kingdom Accreditation Services (UKAS) including for the extraction of core samples from the highway. It is intended to appoint a minimum of 3 providers to the framework agreement subject to there being sufficient tenderers satisfying the criteria laid down within the tender process.

Contracts called-off from the framework agreement will be awarded on a cascade basis, with the tenderer submitting the Most Economically Advantageous Tender being appointed as the first provider to the relevant lot, which will be contacted in the first instance in respect of any service requirements. Should the first provider not have the capacity and/or capability and/or not be willing to provide the services then the second provider and third provider would be contacted in turn. Alternatively, contracting bodies accessing the framework agreement may re-open competition to all providers capable of meeting the requirement within the framework agreement via a ?mini competition? process within the applicable lot(s).

The services provided under the framework agreement will be made available to members and associate members of the Association of Greater Manchester Authorities (AGMA) and other participating authorities and organisational bodies as named within this Contract Notice. The Invitation to Tender documentation contains further details on those organisations intending to use this framework agreement at its outset. The estimated number of cores from all classifications of carriageways and footways to be called-off the framework agreement for indicative purposes only is shown within the Invitation to Tender documentation. None of the named organisations will however be obliged to procure through the framework agreement. Economic operators should note that inclusion on the framework agreement is not a guarantee that any call-off contracts will be awarded.

The framework agreement will initially run for a period of 2 years and will allow for 2 further periods of extension of 12 months each. The maximum duration of the framework agreement will be 4 years.


Additional information: Wigan Council is using the e-procurement portal known as The Chest at https://www.the-chest.org.uk/ to conduct the procurement exercise. To gain access to the tender documents applicants will need to register their details at the following link https://procontract.due-north.com/register. Once registered applicants will be e-mailed a log-in and password which will allow them to gain access to the tender documents. 

This contract notice was submitted for publication in the Offical Journal of the European Union (OJEU) on 15th March 2016 and was published with reference number 2016/S 055-091152 on the 18th March 2016

column41: Removal of Waste from St Mary’s, Isles of Scilly to a Suitable Waste Management Site
column42:
The Contract concerns the remove of municipal solid waste (EWC 20 03 01) in the form of ‘black bag’ waste and shredded bulky waste that has been mechanically treated (EWC 19 12 12), typical of that generated at a Household Waste Recycling Centre (HWRC). It is estimated that the Council generates around 400  tonnes of black bag waste/shredded waste which is to be removed from the Porthmellon Waste Management Site, St Mary’s, Isles of Scilly and this requires transportation to a suitable waste disposal, treatment or recovery site off the islands.

 A contractor is being sought to undertake the following work elements:

1.Load and containerise black bag waste/shredded waste in suitable containers at the Council waste facility at Porthmellon Waste Management Site, Moorwell, St Marys.


2.Transport the containerised materials to the dock at St Marys or an alternative authorised location within St Marys.


3.Loading from the dock and onward marine shipment, in accordance with current UK regulations, from St Marys to an appropriate authorised port.


4.Offloading and onward transport to a suitable licensed waste management facility for the acceptance of the above waste and;


5.Final disposal, recovery or treatment at a suitably licensed waste management facility.

column41: College Of Health Clinical Network, supply of technical and support services for an NHS N3 compliant network and associated services.
column42:
The College of Health http://www.derby.ac.uk/health-and-social-care/ delivers a wide range of Health and Social Care related programmes of study. The Kedleston Road Campus, Derby includes a Clinical Skills Suite http://www.derby.ac.uk/health-and-social-care/choose/clinical-skills-suite/  where health related students can be taught in a realistic hospital setting. Located in the same area is the Health, Lifestyle & Rehabilitation Centre http://www.derby.ac.uk/health-and-social-care/choose/clinical-skills-suite/health-lifestyle-rehabilitation-centre/ where private diagnostic imaging and (soon) counselling services are delivered. The College’s plans include an expansion of the existing services to be delivered to the NHS and an expansion of Health & Social Care related research practice. The Health theme of this part of the Campus continued by the co-location of a GP Practice providing NHS services to University students. 
To support these plans, the University now needs to procure an N3 compliant service for a small stand-alone network within the Kedleston Road Campus from a suitable service provider. The Clinical network will be a separate stand-alone network with all the associated services to meet the NHS Information Governance regime. The University’s internal IT Services department is leading the project to deliver these services and now needs to procure them via this Invitation to Tender 

Please refer to the attached Tender documents.

Suppliers should provide a copy of their Terms and Conditions and Licence Agreement with their Tender submission which will be reviewed and negotiated if required.

The Authority is seeking applications from suitable organisations that are 
interested in tendering for Phase 3 of a works project which involves a series 
of Highway Improvements designed to improve traffic flows, public transport 
movements and pedestrian and cyclist accessibility in the A1058 corridor, a 
link of strategic importance in North Tyneside between Newcastle and Tynemouth


Phase 3 of this project improvements briefly comprise the following: - 
• The redesign of Coast Road’s junctions with Norham Road The replacement of 
the existing Norham Road bridge with a newer, wider structure; 
• Signing amendments including direction signs and speed limit signs;

TUPE related information must be treated as protected data in accordance with the requirements of the Data Protection Act 1998 and must be kept confidential. a)	To undertake to treat the information as confidential and commercially sensitive at all times and take all reasonable steps to prevent any inadvertent disclosure to any third party .

e)	The requirements above apply whether the supplier uploads a tender response to this procurement or not.

Hertfordshire County Council are currently out to procurement for the provision of Independent Domestic Violence Advisors Service (IDVA) in Hertfordshire.
This procurement is a one stage process. Suppliers wishing to take part in this project are invited to ‘express interest’ which will give access to the full procurement documents in the e-tendering system.

Any questions relating to this procurement must be made via correspondence on the website, in accordance with the procurement documents and can be addressed to the main contact as shown in the details above.

This procurement is not being divided in to Lots because the Council wishes to procure an end-to-end service from a single supplier.
Tenderers should be aware that due to the nature of the Services provided, any Contract formed as a result of this procurement process shall be executed as a deed and attested under the common seal of the Council. column41: Payroll Services for University Examiners, Interns & Temporary Employees Contract
column42:
The University of London is proud to announce an opportunity for an experienced and qualified supplier to provide payroll services for the University’s examiners, interns and temporary employees.  We are seeking to award a 3 year contract for payroll services with an estimated aggregate value of between £65,000 and £75,000 pounds Sterling.

The successful supplier in this tender will not only be skilled and experienced in the provision of payroll services.  The supplier we are seeking must work in partnership with the University of London to provide an efficient, high quality and customer service focussed service for our examiners, interns and temporary employees.   The successful supplier will also have the agility and sense of urgency required when providing payroll services to a large group of staff members working on a variety of schedules.

This tender will be conducted electronically and tenderers can register on our e-tendering system Proactis for free here: https://supplierlive.proactisp2p.com/Account/Login.  All tender documents can be found online and communications during the tender period will be managed through the Proactis e-tendering system.  For audit purposes all queries must be raised online through the Proactis messaging servicer ONLY; queries submitted by external e mail or by phone or in person will not be taken and tenderers will be referred to the Proactis online system.  Suppliers are strongly advised to read the tender documents thoroughly before deciding to bid for this contract.

This is a Single Stage Tender.  Suppliers must complete the PQQ and tender documents and return both before 12:00pm on 15 April 2016.  No late tenders will be considered for this procurement exercise.

The University of London is holding a Supplier Engagement Day for suppliers to find out more about the tender and contract.  This event will provide more information about the contract to be awarded and suppliers can meet the University of London International Programmes and Procurement project team members.  Suppliers will also have the opportunity to ask any questions they may have about the tender and contract.  

Tender for Payroll Services for Examiners, Interns & Temporary Employees

	10:00am – 12:30pm
	University of London 
	The Woburn Room
	Malet Street

column41: Better Care Fund - Early Intervention, Rapid Response and Reablement
column42:
The Council of the Isles of Scilly is seeking a delivery partner to co-design and pilot three key elements of its Better Care Fund plan, ensuring that the individual is at the heart of the support they receive.  The delivery partner will demonstrate that they have an excellent understanding of the current service structures in place on Scilly and be able to engage other partners in changing how the existing staff resource is used.  

The delivery partner will play an active role in the newly evolving Isles of Scilly Integrated Care Team and will use their expert knowledge of early intervention and community based rehabilitation services to improve outcomes for the islands’ residents.  

 They will be required to join the developing integrated care team and provide leadership and active case management. They will proactively identify service users who would benefit from a rehabilitative support plan and work with services in planning, delivering and reviewing outcomes.

The elements requiring the co-design and delivery are:

1. Early intervention service
2. Rapid response
3. Reablement pathway design.

This Provision is voluntary and will aim to improve job outcome rates for claimants who have left the Work Programme without a successful outcome, preventing them from becoming longer term unemployed and further detached from the labour market. The Provision will provide intensive support to gain employment which is tailored to the needs of the individual and delivered by an Employment Coach. The Provider is expected to deliver the Provision across the seven local authority areas within the North East LEP boundary. There must be sufficient delivery in each Local Authority area to meet Participant needs. This may include so co-location. The North East LEP area covers: Northumberland – Deep rural areas, market towns and a small urban area – limited public  transport links to remote areas; North Tyneside – Urban, good connectivity; Newcastle upon Tyne – Urban, good connectivity; Gateshead – Urban with large rural areas which have limited public transport links; South Tyneside – Urban, good connectivity; Sunderland – Urban, good connectivity; County Durham – Rural areas and market towns– limited public  transport links to remote areas.

column42:
Development of a miniaturised acoustic smart sensor falls under BRIDGES WP5, Task 5.4 lead by NOC. The deliverable will be the design and build of a suitable system with accompanying documentation to support  system  integration into the glider being designed under the BRIDGES project.
This task will integrate a sensor payload targeted to support surveillance of sea-bed mining activities to monitor the impact of discharges of the unwanted debris and to determine nodule characteristics and associated substrate. 
We require an acoustic specialist to design and build a miniaturised acoustic sensor suitable for installation on the D and UD vehicles (to 5000m depth). This low-power, low-range sensor will be used for purely scientific purposes to characterise sea-bed sediment properties. 
The miniaturized acoustic smart sensor will be designed to obtain information on sea bottom sub-surface layers. The sensing package will consist of: a set of transducers and hydrophones for acoustic transmission and reception in the frequency range of 10-30 KHz; a programmable wideband signal generator; a low power and low noise acquisition system and a set of processing algorithms to extract the different acoustic impedances and sound speed profiles of the sea-bottom layers with a penetration up to 10 meters. 
Technical requirements to allow integration with the BRIDGES glider are given below:
Maximum power consumption during sampling: 25W
Total sampling time at bottom of dive no more than: 1 minute @ 25W
Power should be kept to a minimum to maximise deployment time.
Discrete operation enabled/disabled by external input
Communications: Ethernet TCP/IP and/or RS232
Optional PPS TTL signal from glider control for time synchronization
Externally supplied power, max supply voltage: 48V
Data storage on board (approx. 500 Gb)
Comprehensive technical documentation (including manuals, schematics, data sheets, interface protocols and other as required)
Physical size and weight  to be suitable for Glider operations.  It is expected that the glider will have a total maximum wet payload weight of approx. 5Kg .
Maximum Operating depth :  5000m

Full instructions for registration and use of the system can be found at http://ccs.cabinetoffice.gov.uk/i-am-supplier/respond-tender Once you have registered on the eSourcing Suite, a registered user can express an interest for a specific procurement. This is done by emailing ExpressionOfInterest@ccs.gsi.gov.uk. column42: The Department’s National Transport Model (NTM) provides national-level traffic forecasts and evidence underpinning critical decisions at DfT, and as such its results are subject to increasing interest and scrutiny by external stakeholders including academics and lobby groups. This purchase of the Wider Intellectual Property Rights (IPR) License for the MEPLAN software package, is part of a larger research programme to improve the NTM to meet current needs, including greater geographic detail for Roads analysis and a higher standard of quality control as part of the NTM Next Generation programme. This purchase will enable us to read and update the software code used in NTM and remove the main commercial barrier for sharing NTM by giving us the rights to sub-licence MEPLAN software to external organisations.

column41: ITT243 Waterside Strategic Partner IT Procurement
column42:
The University has committed to creating a new campus for its ever-widening community, in the heart of Northampton. The new Waterside Campus, opening in September 2018, will provide state-of-the-art academic facilities for 15,000 students, additional residential facilities for 1,200 students and leisure facilities open to the local community.  

The innovative £330m Waterside Campus will transform a 58 acre brownfield site in Northampton’s Waterside Enterprise Zone.  The area is in close proximity to the town centre, a short walk away through the town’s Cultural Quarter and past the University’s St John’s Halls of Residences, opened in 2014.

See http://www.watersidecampus.info/ for further information.

The programme is now at a stage where the Information and Communication Technology elements are to be defined and purchased to ensure the campus is fit for purpose when opened and the University’s vision can be effectively supported by the appropriate technology solutions and services.

The University is seeking a technology partner who can work with us at a strategic level. The strategic partner will work with the University to design, develop and implement solutions and will take responsibility for ensuring continuity and integration, so that the University benefits from an holistic approach to the active infrastructure components that are set out below. The University also expects some sharing of risk with the strategic partner in ensuring that components of the overall IT solution work together in a seamless way. 

The University expects to benefit from the experience and resources in research, development and implementation that a strategic partner could provide. The strategic partner will also support the University with the on-going development and innovation of solutions beyond the opening of the new campus in 2018. The strategic partner should also provide measurable and substantial opportunities to students and staff which add value and contribute towards the mission of the University to transform lives and inspire change.

The University of Northampton are seeking  tenders for services and solutions that could be developed and implemented to deliver innovative, efficient and scalable solutions within the new Waterside campus and across the University in support of our strategic plan. 

The IT for Waterside requirements can be split into the following active infrastructure components:

•         Wired Network Solutions
•         Wireless Network solutions
•         Unified Communications
•         Desktop and Mobile Computing
•         Audio Visual Solutions
•         Server and Storage Solutions
•         Security and Compliance

The University is looking for best value in terms of service reach, quality, delivery and cost for the required solutions and therefore wishes to procure a single strategic partner that can demonstrate the ability to offer a technologic...

Additional information: The information and documents for this tender will be accessible from  
https://in-tendhost.co.uk/universityofnorthampton 
Click on Current Tenders link where you can view the project detail, express an interest and register your Organisation with our e-tendering system. Once the registration has been accepted and you have received your login details by e:mail you can login to view and download the PQQ in the My Tenders section of the website.

ASD Evidence and Research Strategy: Building capability within DfT and building on the social and behavioural research evidence base for cross-cutting themes and specific policy projects.
A key objective of SBR is to work with other disciplines to build capability in the use of social research evidence and behavioural insights. SBR is the centre for expertise on BIs in the department and holds specific knowledge of BI applications to the transport context. Through building capability, our aim is to develop knowledge of BI across the DfT and encourage wider and more informed applications of social and behavioural evidence. The Policy Profession in-turn is focussed upon improving BI capacity amongst its members as part of its strategic refresh. 
Furthermore the SBR-led Think People programme reflects how behavioural insights, acting as part of a people centered approach to public policy delivery, have been made a departmental priority by Claire Perry MP, Parliamentary Under Secretary of State, and Philip Rutnam, Permanent Secretary.

column41: Student Materials Pick & Pack and Courier Services Contract
column42:
The University of London and the University of London International Academy are proud to announce an opportunity for an experienced and qualified courier and pick and pack service provider to coordinate and deliver our student materials around the world.  We are seeking to award a 5 year contract for pick and pack and courier services in the estimated aggregate value of between £4million and £6million pounds Sterling.

The successful supplier in this tender will not only be skilled and experienced in international and London courier services and pick and pack services.  The supplier we are seeking must work in partnership with the University of London to provide an efficient, high quality and customer service focussed service for our students.   The successful supplier will also have the systems capability to work with the University’s stock management and financial systems.  

This tender will be conducted electronically and tenderers can register on Proactis for free here: https://supplierlive.proactisp2p.com/Account/Login; look for opportunity ERSP1000130.  All tender documents can be found online and communications during the tender period will be managed through the Proactis e-tendering system.  For audit purposes all queries must be raised online through the Proactis messaging servicer ONLY; queries submitted by external e mail or by phone or in person will not be taken and tenderers will be referred to the Proactis online system.  Suppliers are strongly advised to read the tender documents thoroughly before deciding to bid for this contract.

This is a Single Stage Tender.  Suppliers must complete the PQQ and tender documents and return both before 12:00pm on 14 April 2016.  No late tenders will be considered for this procurement exercise.

The University of London is holding a Supplier Engagement Day for suppliers to find out more about the tender and contract.  This event will provide more information about the contract to be awarded and suppliers can meet the University of London International Programmes and Procurement project team members.  Suppliers will also have the opportunity to ask any questions they may have about the tender and contract.

column31: Future opportunity notice on Contracts Finder
column42:
To develop and rollout a new, secure, online / onscreen Key Stage 2 test for primary children in England (Circa 16,000 schools / 550,000 children).   The supplier must develop a system to be used online and provide a service to cater for schools with limited / no internet access and/or poor IT infrastructure.  

In addition the supplier will need to manage a whole service for the test which includes providing a helpdesk to support schools with technical issues in the system, ensuring that the data captured from the system can feed into other STA data feeds.

The supplier will need to have knowledge of the wide variety of Special Educational Needs in schools and be able to make, and suggest, modifications to the test to cater for these children.

The test will only be focussed on 1-12 times tables; although the length and timing of the test is still to be decided following a wider consultation, it is envisaged that the test will be sat by pupils in May 2017.

This is the first online /onscreen Key Stage 2 test in primary schools and the Standards and Testing Agency are keen to explore all options for the delivery of this contract and will consider using any existing software if it can be fully amended to suit the needs of the test.  It should be noted, however, that any system that is proposed must be able to import and export data with existing STA systems and new systems that may be developed under a new Key Stage 2 test delivery contract in 2018 onwards.

Security requirements are essential and any potential supplier must ensure their services are compliant with the HMG Security Policy Framework in conjunction with current CESG Information Assurance Policy.  As part of this the supplier must be able to demonstrate that:
•	they have achieved, and be able to maintain, independent certification to ISO/IEC 27001.  
•	Will comply with the UK Government Security Classification Policy in respect of Departmental Data being handled in the course of providing this service (https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/government-security-classifications.)  
•	Any electronic transfer methods across public space or cyberspce must be protected via encryption which has been certified to a minimum FIPS 140-2 standard.  This includes and devices / hardware / portable equipment to be used in the delivery of the service
•	Be aware that  IT systems or hosting environments that are to be used for this project shall be subject to an independent IT Health Check using a CESG approved ITHC provider  (more information: https://www.cesg.gov.uk/scheme/penetration-testing)

The above bullets are not inclusive and further information on security requirements will be issued with the invitation to tender.

This will be a 3 year contract with option of further extending for 2 years. Intention is to have supplier in contract for September 2016

Additional information: This requirement will be advertised via the Department for Education’s e-procurement system Redimo2. To prevent any delay in accessing the documentation once this tender goes live, it is recommended that you register as early as possible. Successful registration and selection of relevant Common Procurement Vocabulary (CPV) codes will also ensure that you receive automated notification when any open tenders are published on the portal that match any of those codes.

Registering on Redimo2: www.gov.uk/government/organisations/department-for-education/about/procurement#redimo2. Please note registration is a multi-stage process, please follow the guidance and ensure you allow sufficient time to complete the registration process.

Please contact  commercial.contactpoint@education.gsi.gov.uk if you have any queries regarding registering on Redimo2.

column41: Community of practice for MCP vanguards
column42:
The New Care Models programme is looking to procure a supplier to facilitate and develop a community of practice for multi-specialty community provider (MCP) vanguards.
Communities of practice are groups of practitioners who come together to provide peer support, shared expertise and experience in developing a common purpose.  In this instance, the common purpose is designing and implementing multi-specialty community providers in England.
There are 14 MCP vanguards spread geographically across England.
We are looking for a community of practice that brings together all MCP vanguards and also hosts separate events for North and South regions.
The communities started to form in 15/16 and the supplier will need to build on these existing relationships to deliver an effective community of practice.
The supplier will need to demonstrate effective facilitation and coaching at an executive level with an astute understanding of appropriate subject matter experts that may be appropriate to bring in, providing independent support, advice and challenge to developing vanguards.  Policy awareness and experience of working on large scale organisational change programmes will be especially sought.

column41: Feasibility Study of Eddy Current Inspection of Aluminium Tanker Welds
column42:
Further research is being considered to refine the analysis, look at the effects of fatigue, and undertake large scale testing of tanks, so as to assess the relative safety of non-compliant tankers in their current condition, after proposed modifications, and in comparison to compliant tankers. The work also has the potential to improve the safety and efficiency of all petroleum tankers, and to better regulation.

The research will likely include a peer review of existing work, the commissioning of various tests, detailed engineering analysis and technical assessments of the test and theoretical results, and also of any weld procedures developed for proposed modifications. Research activities are subject to modification in response to findings as the work progresses.

Given the potential impact on fuel supply and road safety, the research is to be undertaken and reported upon as soon as possible - initial work on non-compliant tankers (Phase 1) should be completed by the end of March 2014, and subject to the outcome of Phase 1, and any other factors, further work on non-compliant tankers and any work on modified and/or compliant tankers (Phase 2) should be completed between the end of June 2014 and the end of September 2014.
